<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><U>Experience and Qualifications</U></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;Retired from Pfizer Inc., a
pharmaceutical, consumer and animal products health company, in December 2007:</P> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.22em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#161;
</FONT></SUP>&nbsp;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Vice Chairman (July 2005 to December 2007)</P> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.22em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#161;
</FONT></SUP>&nbsp;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Executive Vice President and Chief Financial Officer (January 1999 to July 2005)</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Mr. Shedlarz spent the majority of his professional career with Pfizer. At the time of his retirement in 2007, Mr. Shedlarz was responsible for operations
including the animal health business, finance, accounting, strategic planning, business development, global sourcing, manufacturing, information systems and human resources, skills that are particularly valuable to the Board given his role as chair
of the Finance and Risk Management Committee. Mr. Shedlarz also brings to our Board considerable international business and leadership experience he gained while at Pfizer.</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><U>Public and Other Key Directorships</U></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pitney Bowes, Inc. (May 2001 to present)</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;Teachers Insurance and Annuity
Association Board of Trustees (March 2007 to present)</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><U>Education</U></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;Bachelor&#146;s degree in economics and mathematics from Oakland/Michigan State University</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;Masters of Business
Administration degree in finance and accounting from the New York University, Leonard N. Stern School of Business</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">29 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc118343_14"></A>NON-EMPLOYEE DIRECTOR COMPENSATION </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>The Hershey Company Directors&#146; Compensation Plan </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We
maintain a Directors&#146; Compensation Plan that is designed to: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Attract and retain highly qualified, non-employee directors; and </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Align the interests of non-employee directors with those of our stockholders by paying a portion of non-employee compensation in units representing shares of our Common Stock. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Directors who are employees of the Company receive no additional compensation for their service on our Board. Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey, our current Chairman of the
Board, President and CEO, is the only employee of the Company who also served as a director during 2015 and thus received no additional compensation for his Board service. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Board targets non-employee director compensation at the 50<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP> percentile of compensation paid to
directors at a peer group of companies we call the 2015 Peer Group. Information about the 2015 Peer Group is included on page 48 of the Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis. Each year, with the assistance of the Compensation Committee and the
Compensation Committee&#146;s compensation consultant, the Board reviews the compensation paid to directors at companies in the current peer group to determine whether any changes to non-employee director compensation are warranted. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">As a result of its review in December 2014, the Board determined that no changes to non-employee director compensation were warranted for 2015. However,
effective April&nbsp;2, 2015, in connection with the establishment of the Lead Independent Director position, and upon the recommendation of the Compensation Committee, the Board approved an annual fee of $25,000 for the Lead Independent Director,
to be paid in addition to the annual retainer for non-employee directors. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Accordingly, compensation paid to non-employee directors in 2015 was as follows:
</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

of non-employee director compensation in October 2015 and determined that no changes to any of the compensation elements were warranted for 2016. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">30 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Payment of Annual Retainer, Lead Independent Director Fee and Committee Chair Fees </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The annual retainer and any applicable Lead Independent Director or committee chair fees for all non-employee directors are paid in quarterly installments on
the 15<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th </SUP>day of March, June, September and December, or the prior business day if the 15<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP> is not a business day. Non-employee directors may
elect to receive all or a portion of the annual retainer in cash or in Common Stock. Non-employee directors may also elect to defer receipt of all or a portion of the retainer, Lead Independent Director fee or committee chair fees until the date
their membership on the Board ends. Lead Independent Director and committee chair fees that are not deferred are paid only in cash. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Non-employee directors
choosing to defer all or a portion of their retainer, Lead Independent Director fee or committee chair fees may invest the deferred amounts in two ways: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">In a cash account that values the performance of the investment based upon the performance of one or more third-party investment funds selected by the director from among the mutual funds or other investment options
available to all employees participating in our 401(k) Plan. Amounts invested in the cash account are paid only in cash. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">In a deferred common stock unit account that we value according to the performance of our Common Stock, including reinvested dividends. Amounts invested in the deferred common stock unit account are paid in shares of
Common Stock. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Restricted Stock Units </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">RSUs are granted quarterly to non-employee directors on the first day of January, April, July and October. In 2015, the number of RSUs granted in each quarter
was determined by dividing $33,750 by the average closing price of a share of our Common Stock on the New York Stock Exchange (&#147;NYSE&#148;) on the last three trading days preceding the grant date. RSUs awarded to non-employee directors vest one
year after the date of grant, or earlier upon termination of the director&#146;s membership on the Board by reason of retirement (termination of service from the Board after the director&#146;s
60<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP> birthday), death or disability, for any reason after a Change in Control as defined in our Executive Benefits Protection Plan (Group 3A) (&#147;EBPP 3A&#148;), or under such other
circumstances as the Board may determine. Vested RSUs are payable to directors in shares of Common Stock or, at the option of the director, can be deferred as common stock units under the Directors&#146; Compensation Plan until the director&#146;s
membership on the Board ends. Dividend equivalent units are credited at regular rates on the RSUs during the restriction period and, upon vesting of the RSUs, are payable in shares of Common Stock or deferred as common stock units together with any
RSUs the director has deferred. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">As of March&nbsp;7, 2016, Messrs. Davis, Malcolm, Mead, Nevels, Ridge and Shedlarz and Ms.&nbsp;Arway had attained
retirement age for purposes of the vesting of RSUs. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Other Compensation, Reimbursements and Programs </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Board occasionally establishes committees of limited duration for special purposes. The Board will consider paying additional compensation to non-employee
directors who serve on special committees, generally $1,250 per meeting, if the special committee holds six or more meetings, each lasting one hour or more. No director received compensation for service on a special committee in 2015. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We reimburse our directors for travel and other out-of-pocket expenses they incur when attending Board and committee meetings and for minor incidental expenses
they incur when performing </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">31 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">
directors&#146; services. We also provide reimbursement for at least one director continuing education program each year. Directors receive travel accident insurance while traveling on the
Company&#146;s business and receive discounts on the purchase of our products to the same extent and on the same terms as our employees. Directors also are eligible to participate in the Company&#146;s Gift Matching Program. Under the Gift Matching
Program, the Company will match, upon a director&#146;s request, contributions made by the director to one or more charitable organizations, on a dollar-for-dollar basis up to a maximum aggregate contribution of $5,000 annually. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Stock Ownership Guidelines </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Pursuant to the Board&#146;s
Corporate Governance Guidelines, non-employee directors are expected to own shares of Common Stock having a value equal to at least four times the annual retainer. Each non-employee director has until January&nbsp;1 of the year following his or her
fifth anniversary of becoming a director to satisfy the guideline. The Compensation Committee reviews the stock ownership guidelines annually to ensure they are aligned with external market comparisons. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>2015 Director Compensation </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The following table and
explanatory footnotes provide information with respect to the compensation paid or provided to non-employee directors during 2015: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The following table sets forth the portion of fees earned or paid in cash or Common Stock, and the portion deferred with respect to retainers and fees earned during 2015: </TD></TR></TABLE>

Group, Inc. had sole voting and investment power over 8,404,140 shares of Common Stock. The filing indicated that Vanguard Group, Inc. is a parent holding company or control person in accordance with Rule&nbsp;13d-1(b)(1)(ii)(G) and that various
persons have the right to receive or the power to direct the receipt of dividends from, or the proceeds from the sale of, our Common Stock. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Ownership of Other Company Securities </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Certain directors
and NEOs hold Company securities not reflected in the beneficial ownership table above because they will not convert, or cannot be converted, to shares of Common Stock within 60 days of our March&nbsp;7, 2016 Record Date. These securities include:
</P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">*</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Director </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Information Regarding Our Controlling Stockholder </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In 1909, Milton S. and Catherine S. Hershey established a trust having as its sole beneficiary Milton Hershey School, a non-profit school for the full-time
care and education of disadvantaged children located in Hershey, Pennsylvania. Hershey Trust Company, a state-chartered trust company, is trustee of the Milton Hershey School Trust. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In its capacity as trustee for the Milton Hershey School Trust, Hershey Trust Company is our controlling stockholder. In this capacity, it will have the right
to cast 8.2% of all of the votes entitled to be cast on matters requiring the vote of the Common Stock voting separately and 81.4% of all of the votes entitled to be cast on matters requiring the vote of the Common Stock and Class B Common Stock
voting together. The board of directors of Hershey Trust Company, with the approval of the board of managers (governing body) of Milton Hershey School, decides how funds held by Hershey Trust Company, as trustee for the Milton Hershey School Trust,
will be invested. The board of directors of Hershey Trust Company generally decides how shares of The Hershey Company held by Hershey Trust Company, as trustee for the Milton Hershey School Trust, will be voted. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">36 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">As of the Record Date, Hershey Trust Company also held 199,000 shares of our Common Stock as investments. The
board of directors or management of Hershey Trust Company decides how these shares will be voted. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In all, Hershey Trust Company, as trustee for the Milton
Hershey School Trust and as direct owner of investment shares, will be entitled to vote 12,902,921 shares of our Common Stock and 60,612,012 shares of our Class B Common Stock at the Annual Meeting. Stated in terms of voting power, Hershey Trust
Company will have the right to cast 8.4% of all of the votes entitled to be cast on matters requiring the vote of the Common Stock voting separately and 81.4% of all of the votes entitled to be cast on matters requiring the vote of the Common Stock
and Class B Common Stock voting together at the Annual Meeting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Our certificate of incorporation contains the following important provisions regarding our
Class B Common Stock: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">All holders of Class B Common Stock, including Hershey Trust Company, as trustee for Milton Hershey School, may convert any of their Class B Common Stock shares into shares of our Common Stock at any time on a
share-for-share basis. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">All shares of Class B Common Stock will automatically be converted to shares of Common Stock on a share-for-share basis if Hershey Trust Company, as trustee for Milton Hershey School, or any successor trustee, or Milton
Hershey School, as appropriate, ceases to hold more than 50% of the total Class B Common Stock shares outstanding and at least 15% of the total Common Stock and Class B Common Stock shares outstanding. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">We must obtain the approval of Hershey Trust Company, as trustee for Milton Hershey School, or any successor trustee, or Milton Hershey School, as appropriate, before we issue any Common Stock or take any other action
that would deprive Hershey Trust Company, as trustee for Milton Hershey School, or any successor trustee, or Milton Hershey School, as appropriate, of the ability to cast a majority of the votes on any matter where the Class B Common Stock is
entitled to vote, either separately as a class or together with any other class. </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">37 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc118343_16"></A>AUDIT COMMITTEE REPORT </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>To Our Stockholders: </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Audit Committee is currently
comprised of four directors, each of whom is considered independent under the NYSE Rules and the rules and regulations of the SEC. The Board has determined that each member of the Audit Committee is financially literate and that each of Messrs.
Davis, Mead and Nevels qualifies as an &#147;audit committee financial expert,&#148; as that term is defined under the rules promulgated by the SEC. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Our
role as the Audit Committee is to assist the Board in its oversight of: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The integrity of the Company&#146;s financial statements; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The performance of the independent auditors and the Company&#146;s internal audit function. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10.5pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Audit
Committee operates under a written charter that was last reviewed by the Audit Committee on December&nbsp;1, 2015. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Our duties as an Audit Committee
include overseeing the Company&#146;s management, internal auditors and independent auditors in their performance of the following functions, for which they are responsible: </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:4%; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Management </P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

communications with the Audit Committee concerning independence; and </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Discussed with the independent auditors their independence from the Company. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We are not employees of the
Company and are not performing the functions of auditors or accountants. We are not responsible as an Audit Committee or individually to conduct &#147;field work&#148; or other types of auditing or accounting reviews or procedures or to set auditor
independence standards. In carrying out our duties as Audit Committee members, we have relied on the information provided to us by management and the independent auditors. Consequently, we do not assure that the audit of the Company&#146;s financial
statements has been carried out in accordance with generally accepted auditing standards, that the financial statements are presented in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles or that the Company&#146;s auditors are in fact
&#147;independent.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Based on the reports and discussions described in this report, and subject to the limitations on our role and responsibilities as
an Audit Committee referred to above and in our charter, we recommended to the Board that the audited financial statements be included in the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, filed with the SEC on
February&nbsp;26, 2016. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:54%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Submitted by the Audit Committee:</B> </P>

LLP</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">as&nbsp;the Company&#146;s independent auditors for
2016</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>

so, the Board, upon the Audit Committee&#146;s recommendation, has determined to submit the Audit Committee&#146;s appointment of KPMG LLP as our independent auditors to stockholders for ratification as a matter of good corporate governance. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Audit Committee&#146;s appointment of KPMG LLP as the Company&#146;s independent auditors for 2016 will be considered ratified if a majority of the shares
of the Common Stock and Class B Common Stock (voting together without regard to class) present and entitled to vote at the Annual Meeting are voted for the proposal. If stockholders do not ratify the appointment of KPMG LLP as the Company&#146;s
independent auditors for 2016, the Audit Committee will reconsider its appointment. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Representatives of KPMG&nbsp;LLP will attend the Annual Meeting, will
have the opportunity to make a statement, if they so desire, and will respond to questions. </P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><A NAME="toc118343_19"></A>COMPENSATION DISCUSSION&nbsp;&amp; ANALYSIS
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc118343_20"></A>EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">This section discusses and analyzes the decisions we made concerning the compensation of our named executive officers (&#147;NEOs&#148;) for 2015, including
our former interim Principal Financial Officer (&#147;PFO&#148;). It also describes the process for determining executive compensation and the factors considered in determining the amount of compensation awarded to our NEOs. The NEOs for 2015
include the following: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Executive Summary </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>2015 Highlights </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Hershey Company (the &#147;Company&#148;), headquartered in Hershey, Pa., is a global confectionery leader known for bringing goodness to the world through
its chocolate, sweets, mints and other great-tasting snacks. The Company has approximately 21,000 employees around the world who work every day to deliver delicious, quality products. The Company has more than 80 brands that drive approximately $7.4
billion in annual revenues. Building on its core business, the Company is expanding its portfolio to include a broader range of delicious snacks. The Company remains focused on growing its presence in key international markets while continuing to
extend its competitive advantage in North America. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In January 2015, we announced high expectations for the Company, which we also incorporated into our
2015 incentive programs: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Volume-driven, full-year 2015 net sales to increase 5.5% to 7.5% from 2014; and </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">2015 adjusted earnings per share-diluted<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(1)</SUP> to increase 8% to 10% from 2014. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="line-height:8.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1.00pt solid #000000;width:21%">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(1)</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">While we report our financial results in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles (&#147;GAAP&#148;), we also use non-GAAP financial measures within Management&#146;s Discussion and Analysis in the
2015 Annual Report on Form 10-K that accompanies this Proxy Statement in order to provide additional information to investors to facilitate the comparison of past and present performance. Some of the financial targets under our short- and long-term
incentive programs are also based on non-GAAP financial measures. Non-GAAP financial measures are used by management in evaluating results of operations internally and in assessing the impact of known trends and uncertainties on our business, but
they are not intended to replace the presentation of financial results in accordance with GAAP. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Adjusted earnings per share-diluted is a non-GAAP performance measure. We define adjusted earnings per share-diluted as diluted earnings per share of the Company&#146;s common stock (&#147;Common Stock&#148;), excluding
business realignment charges, asset impairment charges, costs relating to business and asset acquisitions and disposals, loss on early extinguishment of debt, and non-service related components of our pension expense (income). </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">42 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Actual results for 2015 were as follows: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g118343g96x06.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Because we did not meet our expectations, our NEOs earned significantly below-target performance stock unit
(&#147;PSU&#148;) payouts and annual cash incentive awards, further reinforcing our pay-for-performance philosophy. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Hershey Has Strong
Pay-for-Performance Alignment </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation and Executive Organization Committee (the &#147;Compensation Committee&#148;) of our Board of Directors
(the &#147;Board&#148;) has oversight responsibility for our executive compensation framework and for aligning our executive&#146;s pay with the Company&#146;s performance. We believe we have a strong pay-for-performance alignment because a
significant portion of each NEO&#146;s target total direct compensation is tied to the financial performance of the Company as well as shareholder returns. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In 2015, approximately 86% of our CEO&#146;s and 71% of our other NEOs&#146; target total direct compensation was variable and tied to Company performance,
including a substantial portion tied to shareholder value. Specifically, 50% of our PSUs were tied to Total Shareholder Return (&#147;TSR&#148;). Combined with the other financial and strategic metrics that determine our NEOs&#146; compensation, we
have aligned our executive compensation program with the long-term interests of our stockholders.</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Over the last three years, we have delivered a TSR of
31.9%, which is at the 9<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP> percentile of our Financial Peer Group described on pages&nbsp;53 and 54. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g118343g49_06.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">43 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Because our TSR metric was below threshold for the 2013-2015 PSU cycle, our NEOs received a 0% payout for this
metric, significantly reducing their overall PSU payout, as described in more detail on page 54. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Our Stockholders Strongly Approve of Our Pay Practices
</I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Last year, our stockholders overwhelmingly approved our &#147;say-on-pay&#148; resolution, with more than 94% of the votes cast by the holders of
Common Stock and more than 99% of the combined votes cast by the holders of the Common Stock and Class B Common Stock voting in favor. Our approach to executive compensation in 2015 was substantially the same as the approach stockholders approved in
2014. In keeping with the preference expressed by our stockholders at the 2011 Annual Meeting of Stockholders, our Board has committed to having an annual &#147;say-on-pay&#148; vote as described on page 81. We plan to ask stockholders to express a
preference for the frequency of the &#147;say-on-pay&#148; vote at our 2017 Annual Meeting of Stockholders. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We believe our compensation and governance
policies and practices are significant drivers of our stockholder support. These policies and practices include: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Pay for performance.</B> A substantial percentage of each of our NEO&#146;s target total direct compensation is variable, performance-based compensation. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Performance measures support strategic objectives.</B> The performance measures we use for our variable, performance-based compensation reflect strategic and operating objectives, creating long-term value for our
stockholders. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Appropriate risk-taking.</B> We set performance goals that consider our publicly-announced financial expectations, which we believe will encourage appropriate risk taking. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>No tax gross-ups.</B> We do not provide tax gross-ups, except for relocation expenses. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>&#147;Double-trigger&#148; benefits in the event of a change in control.</B> In the event of a change in control, the payment of severance benefits and the acceleration of vesting of time-based long-term incentive
awards are &#147;double-trigger&#148; benefits. The severance payments and accelerated vesting of continuing incentive awards will not occur unless there is also a qualifying termination of employment upon or after the change in control.
</TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>No re-pricings or exchanges of underwater stock options.</B> Our stockholder-approved Equity and Incentive Compensation Plan (&#147;EICP&#148;) prohibits re-pricing or exchange of underwater stock options without
stockholder approval. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Significant stock ownership guidelines.</B> Our NEOs and other executives are required to accumulate and hold stock equal to a multiple of base salary. If an executive has not met his or her ownership requirement in
a timely manner, the executive is required to retain a portion of shares received under long-term incentive awards until the requirements are met. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Anti-hedging policy.</B> Our NEOs, directors and other insiders are prohibited from entering into hedging transactions related to our stock. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Protective covenants.</B> For the protection of the Company, we require our NEOs to enter into an Employee Confidentiality and Restrictive Covenant Agreement (&#147;ECRCA&#148;) as a condition of receipt of long-term
incentive awards. Failure to comply with the ECRCA may subject the employee to cancellation of awards and a requirement to repay amounts received from awards. </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">44 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc118343_21"></A>The Role and Philosophy of the Compensation Committee </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee has primary responsibility for making compensation decisions for our NEOs other than our CEO. Our CEO&#146;s compensation is
approved by the independent members of the Board based on the recommendations of the Compensation Committee. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee operates under a
charter approved by the Board. The Compensation Committee uses information from Mercer&nbsp;(US)&nbsp;Inc. (&#147;Mercer&#148;), the Compensation Committee&#146;s independent executive compensation consultant, input from our CEO (except for matters
regarding his own pay) and assistance from our Human Resources Department to make decisions and to conduct its annual review of the Company&#146;s executive compensation program. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee works with a rolling agenda, with its heaviest workload occurring during the first quarter of the year. During this quarter,
decisions are made with respect to annual and long-term incentives earned based on the prior year&#146;s performance and target compensation levels are finalized for the current year. The Compensation Committee also reviews and approves this
Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis. During the second and third quarters, the Compensation Committee reviews materials relating to peer group composition, tally sheets, competitive pay analysis and other information that forms the
foundation for future decisions. The Compensation Committee uses the third and fourth quarters to finalize decisions relating to the peer group and compensation plan design for use in the upcoming year. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The philosophy of our executive compensation program is to provide a compelling, dynamic, market-based total compensation program tied to performance and
aligned with our stockholders&#146; interests. Our goal is to ensure the Company has the talent it needs to maintain sustained long-term performance for our stockholders, employees and communities. The guiding principles that help us achieve this
goal are: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Recruit and retain. </B>Our program is designed to be market competitive and flexible to recruit and retain top talent for our critical roles. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Pay for performance.</B> A significant portion of our executives&#146; compensation is tied to the performance of our Company, rewarding executives for both short-term and long-term progress towards our strategic and
operational goals. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Aligned with strategy.</B> Our compensation program is aligned with the strategies of our Company. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Aligned with stockholders.</B> Our compensation program, through both design and payouts, is aligned with the long-term interests of our stockholders. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Reinforce robust succession planning.</B> Our compensation program plays a key role in making sure we have the talent we need for long-term success and to deliver our Company strategies. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Data-driven decision making.</B> We design our executive compensation program and make pay decisions considering a balance of information. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Compensation Advisor Independence </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Under its engagement
letter with the Compensation Committee, Mercer has acknowledged that the firm is retained by and performs its services for the Compensation Committee while working with management to provide advice, counsel and recommendations that reinforce the
Company&#146;s business strategy, economics, organization and management style. Mercer has provided and continues to provide services and products to the Company in addition to its work for the Compensation Committee, including services related to
global compensation consulting and surveys for various geographies. Mercer and its affiliates also provide products and services to the Company that are unrelated to compensation, including expatriate consulting services (provided by Mercer),
international benefits </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">45 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">
consulting and claims processing services (provided by Mercer) and property and casualty insurance consulting services (provided by Marsh USA Inc. and Marsh INSCO LLC). The Compensation Committee
reviews all fees for services related to executive and director compensation provided by Mercer to the Compensation Committee, as well as fees for compensation-related products and services provided to the Company. The Compensation Committee has no
role in the engagement of Mercer or Mercer affiliates that provide products or services to the Company that are unrelated to compensation; however, the Compensation Committee reviews the fees for such products and services concurrently with its
review of compensation-related fees paid to Mercer. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Fees paid to Mercer and its affiliates for services provided in 2015 related to executive and director
compensation totaled $372,745. Fees paid to Mercer and its affiliates for other services provided in 2015 were as follows: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="76%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee also received and discussed with Mercer its letter to the Compensation Committee addressing factors
relevant under the Securities Exchange Commission (&#147;SEC&#148;) and New York Stock Exchange (&#147;NYSE&#148;) rules in assessing Mercer&#146;s independence from management and whether Mercer&#146;s work for the Compensation Committee has raised
any conflicts of interest, as well as Mercer&#146;s belief that no conflict of interest exists and that it serves as an independent advisor to the Compensation Committee. The factors addressed included the extent of any business or personal
relationships with any member of the Compensation Committee or any executive officer of the Company; Mercer&#146;s and its affiliates&#146; provision of other services to the Company; the level of fees received from the Company as a percentage of
total revenue of each of Mercer and Mercer&#146;s parent company; the policies and procedures employed by Mercer to avoid conflicts of interest; and any ownership of Company stock by individuals employed by Mercer to advise the Compensation
Committee. The Compensation Committee considered these factors before selecting or receiving advice from Mercer, and after considering these and other factors in their totality, the Compensation Committee identified no conflicts of interest with
respect to Mercer&#146;s advice. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In establishing compensation levels and awards for executive officers other than our CEO, the Compensation Committee
takes into consideration the recommendations of Mercer and the Human Resources Department, evaluations by our CEO of each officer&#146;s individual performance and Company performance. The Compensation Committee evaluates director compensation
primarily on the basis of peer group data used for benchmarking director compensation provided by Mercer. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">46 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc118343_22"></A>Compensation Components </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10.5pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Our executive compensation program includes the following key elements: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:9pt" ALIGN="center">

 COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Element</FONT></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:1pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #999999; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #999999">&nbsp;</TD>

<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Design</FONT></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:1pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD>

<P STYLE="font-size:1pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #999999; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #999999">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #999999; padding-right:8pt"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT
 COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Key 2015 Actions</FONT></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:1pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:9pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; padding-left:8pt"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Base Salary</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top">Fixed compensation component. Reviewed annually and adjusted as appropriate.</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top">Intended to attract and retain executives with proven skills and leadership abilities that will enable us to be successful.</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #3f000b; padding-right:8pt">Each NEO, with the exception of Ms. Little, received an increase to their base salary in the beginning of the year consistent with how the Company sets compensation as
described beginning on page&nbsp;48.</TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#bfbfbf" STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:9pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; padding-left:8pt"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Annual Incentive Award</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top">Variable, performance-based compensation component. Payable based on business results and individual performance.</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top">Intended to motivate and reward executives for successful execution of strategic priorities.</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #3f000b; padding-right:8pt">Targets as a percentage of base salary were established at the beginning of 2015 for each NEO and at the time of hire for Ms. Little. Mr. Bilbrey also received a target
increase upon his appointment as Chairman of the Board. No changes were made to the plan design from the previous year.</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:9pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b; padding-left:8pt"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Long-Term Incentive Awards</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b">Variable, performance-based compensation component. Typically granted annually as a combination of PSUs and stock options. The value of amounts actually earned depend on Company and stock
price performance.</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b">Intended to motivate and reward executives for long-term Company financial performance and enhanced long-term stockholder value by balancing compensation opportunity and risk, while
encouraging sustained performance and retention.</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b; padding-right:8pt">Targets as a percentage of base salary were established at the beginning of 2015 for each NEO and at the time of hire for Ms. Little. The
plan design remained consistent with the previous year.</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">47 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The following charts illustrate the weighting of base salary, annual incentive awards and long-term incentive
awards at target for our CEO and our other NEOs during 2015: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g118343g78h48.jpg" ALT="LOGO">

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(1)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s target annual cash incentive award was initially set at 140% of base salary in January 2015. Upon his appointment as Chairman of the Board, Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s target increased to 150%. The
above calculation uses the proration of Mr.&nbsp;
Bilbrey&#146;s incentive targets to calculate his annual cash incentive. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc118343_23"></A>Setting Compensation </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee&#146;s annual compensation review for 2015 included an analysis of data, comparing the Company&#146;s executive and director
compensation levels against a peer group of publicly-held consumer products companies. Mercer provides the Compensation Committee with advice, counsel and recommendations with respect to the composition of the peer group and competitive data used
for benchmarking our compensation program. The Compensation Committee uses this and other information provided by Mercer to reach an independent recommendation regarding compensation to be paid to our CEO. The Compensation Committee&#146;s final
recommendation is then given to the independent directors of our Board for review and final approval. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In prior years, the Company had two separate peer
groups, which we referred to as our Compensation Peer Group and our Financial Peer Group. In 2014, the Compensation Committee decided to utilize one common peer group for 2015 (the &#147;2015 Peer Group&#148;). Companies in the 2015 Peer Group used
to benchmark executive and director pay levels for 2015 are: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="51%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="47%"></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Brown-Forman Corporation</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">Kellogg Company</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">

<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">Kraft Foods Group</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">ConAgra Foods, Inc.</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">McCormick &amp; Company, Inc.</TD></TR>

<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">The Clorox Company</TD></TR>

<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">General Mills, Inc.</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">The J. M. Smucker Company</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Hormel Foods Corporation</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee selected these companies after reviewing publicly-held companies offering products/services similar
to ours, with annual revenues within a range of approximately one-half to two and one-half times our annual revenue (with the exception of Mondelez International whom we also consider a peer company for executive talent) and market capitalization
within a reasonable range of our market capitalization. The 2015 Peer Group was composed of companies with annual revenues ranging from $3.9 billion to $35.2 billion (measured as of the most recent fiscal year end) and market capitalization ranging
from $1.6 billion to $63.8 billion (measured in the second quarter of </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">48 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">
2014). Hershey&#146;s 2013 annual revenue of $7.2 billion and third-quarter 2014 market capitalization of $21.7 billion were at the 47<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP> and
75<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP> percentiles, respectively. Except for Mondelez International, all of the companies in our 2015 Peer Group were included in our 2014 Compensation Peer Group. Energizer Holdings, Inc. and
Hillshire Brands, included in 2014, were not included in the 2015 Peer Group due to a split and a merger, respectively, occurring in 2014. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Data from the
2015 Peer Group was supplemented by composite data from consumer products companies ranging in size from $3 billion to $17 billion in approximate annual sales. This information was included in three national surveys conducted by Aon Hewitt, Mercer
and Towers Watson. The survey composite data provided us with broader, industry-specific information regarding pay levels at consumer products companies for our NEOs. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee reviewed a report summarizing compensation levels at the 25<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP>, 50<SUP
STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP> and 75<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP> percentiles of the 2015 Peer Group and the survey composite data for positions comparable to those held by each of our NEOs. The
Compensation Committee also reviewed a report comparing the target total cash compensation (base salary plus target annual incentive) and target total direct compensation (base salary plus target annual incentive plus target long-term incentive) for
each of the NEOs against these benchmarks. For retention and competitive considerations, the Company targets each NEO&#146;s total cash compensation and total direct compensation levels around the
50<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP> percentile of the 2015 Peer Group data or survey composite data applicable to his or her position. The Compensation Committee&#146;s final determinations with respect to base salary, target
annual incentive compensation and target long-term incentive compensation reflect consideration of the Company&#146;s and the NEO&#146;s performance, internal comparisons and other factors the Compensation Committee deems appropriate. As a result of
these factors, the target total cash compensation and target total direct compensation of our NEOs in 2015 was generally set around the applicable median. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">During 2015, the Compensation Committee received detailed tally sheets prepared by management. Each tally sheet captures comprehensive compensation, benefits
and stock ownership data. The tally sheets provide the Compensation Committee with a complete picture of each executive&#146;s current and projected compensation and the amount of each element of compensation or other benefit the executive would
receive in the event of voluntary or involuntary termination, retirement, disability, death, or upon change in control. The Compensation Committee considers this information, as well as the benchmark information, when making compensation decisions.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc118343_24"></A>Base Salary </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Base salary
is the largest fixed component of our executive compensation program and is determined by considering the relative importance of the position, the competitive marketplace and the individual&#146;s performance, responsibilities and experience. Salary
reviews are generally conducted annually at the beginning of the year. Each NEO&#146;s base salary is compared to internal and external references. Base salary adjustments, if any, are made after considering market references, Company performance
against financial goals and individual performance. CEO performance is evaluated by the Compensation Committee and independent members of the Board. The CEO evaluates the performance of his direct reports, including all NEOs except interim officers,
and reviews his recommendations for salary adjustments with the Compensation Committee prior to its approval of the base salary for each NEO. If a NEO has responsibility for a particular business unit, the business unit&#146;s financial results also
will be strongly considered. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">49 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">On the basis of the foregoing considerations, the Compensation Committee, and all independent directors in the
case of our CEO, approved base salaries for 2015 as follows: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc118343_25"></A>Annual Incentives </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Our
NEOs are eligible to receive an annual cash incentive award under the One Hershey Incentive Program (&#147;OHIP&#148;), a program established under our EICP. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The OHIP links the NEO&#146;s payout opportunity to measures he or she can affect most directly. For 2015, our CEO and all employees reporting directly to him,
including the NEOs, had common financial objectives tied to total Company performance consistent with their responsibility to manage the entire Company. Total Company performance targets are established in the context of our announced expectations
for financial performance, prior year results and market conditions. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">For 2015, our NEOs were eligible to earn individual OHIP awards, expressed as a
percentage of base salary, contingent upon attainment of Company and individual performance objectives. Each of the NEOs was eligible to receive an OHIP award based on the following target percentages: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In determining the target OHIP percentage for each of the NEOs (excluding interim officers), the Compensation Committee, and the independent directors in the
case of our CEO, considered the </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">50 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">
value of target total cash compensation against market references. For each of the NEOs, in 2015 the target total cash compensation fell in the second and third quartiles of target total cash
compensation for comparable positions. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In general, the final OHIP award is determined by multiplying the NEO&#146;s base salary, the applicable target
percentage and performance scores ranging from 0% to 200% based on Company and individual performance. The Company performance goals are established at the beginning of each year by the Compensation Committee. Individual performance goals also are
established at that time, or at the time of hire if later. If performance scores exceed the target objectives, a NEO may receive an OHIP payout greater than his or her target award value. If performance scores are below the target objectives, the
NEO&#146;s OHIP payout will be below his or her target award value, subject to no award if performance is below threshold levels. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">For 2015, Company
financial performance metrics accounted for 65% of each NEO&#146;s target award under the program. The remaining 35% was based upon individual performance toward achievement of up to five individual performance goals focused on strategic priorities
applicable to the NEO&#146;s position, but tied to the overall Company&#146;s top priorities for the year. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>2015 OHIP Performance Targets and Results

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Adjusted earnings per share-diluted is a non-GAAP performance measure. For more information regarding how we define adjusted earnings per share-diluted and our use of non-GAAP performance measures, please see footnote

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(2)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Operating cash flow is a non-GAAP performance measure. We define operating cash flow as the average of cash from operations less pension contributions and commodities hedging transactions, measured in five 12-month
periods ending on the last day of fiscal year 2014 and each quarter of fiscal year 2015. For more information regarding our use of non-GAAP performance measures, please see footnote (1) on page 42. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We achieved below-target performance in net sales, adjusted earnings&nbsp;per&nbsp;share-diluted and operating cash flow. As a result, 65% of the 2015 OHIP
award for each NEO was based on the Company performance score of 47.15%. The remainder of the OHIP award was determined by individual performance ratings. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Following the close of 2015, the Compensation Committee provided the independent directors with an assessment of Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s 2015 performance and
achievement relative to his individual performance goals. The individual performance goals for Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey centered on delivery of the Company&#146;s financial goals, strategic leadership and portfolio and geographic expansion. Although our
financial results were below target due to challenging industry conditions in the category and the negative impact of foreign </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">51 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">
exchange fluctuations, Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey delivered on his strategic leadership and portfolio expansion goals including growing in key geographies, capturing significant cost savings, delivering
above-target innovation, successfully integrating acquisitions, succession planning and diversity efforts. Thus, the Compensation Committee recommended to the independent directors, and the independent directors agreed, that Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey earned
an individual performance award of $464,092, resulting in a total OHIP payout of $1,005,930, as shown in the table below. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Ms.&nbsp;Little, our CFO, had
individual performance goals that included expanding the Company&#146;s global financial capabilities, delivering process improvements and efficiencies, and expanding the mergers and acquisitions organization integration capability. For
Ms.&nbsp;Buck, President, North America, the individual performance goals centered on delivering the North America financial plan, increasing innovation contribution and strategic leadership of our core North American businesses. The individual
performance goals for Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day, Senior Vice President, Chief Supply Chain Officer, focused on designing a supply chain network to enable growth and delivering enterprise margin expansion. For Ms.&nbsp;Turner, Senior Vice President,
General Counsel and Secretary, the individual performance goals included architecting a global government relations strategy and developing legal capabilities in the Company&#146;s key geographies. Mr.&nbsp;McConville, Vice President, Chief
Accounting Officer, was charged with the responsibility for overseeing the Company&#146;s financial statements during the period he was interim PFO. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey provided the Compensation Committee with his assessment of each NEO&#146;s 2015 performance and achievement in relation to their performance
goals. Based upon the results for each of our NEOs, Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey recommended, and the Compensation Committee approved, the individual performance awards and total OHIP payouts as shown in the table below. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Based upon a 65% weight for the Company financial score of 47.15% of target and a 35% weight for the individual performance award, our NEOs earned the
following 2015 OHIP awards: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
